(fifthQuint)Capecitabine and Pegylated Interferon Alfa-2a in Treating Patients With Recurrent or Progressive Brain Metastases Due to Breast Cancer.

 OBJECTIVES: Primary - Determine the efficacy of capecitabine and pegylated interferon alfa-2a, in terms of 6-month neurologic progression-free rate, in patients with recurrent or progressive brain metastases secondary to breast cancer.

 Secondary - Determine the toxicity spectrum of this regimen in these patients.

 - Determine the time to neurologic progression and overall survival of patients treated with this regimen.

 OUTLINE: This is an open-label, multicenter study.

 Patients receive oral capecitabine twice daily on days 1-14 and pegylated interferon alfa-2a subcutaneously on days 1, 8, and 15.

 Treatment repeats every 3 weeks for at least 6 months in the absence of disease progression or unacceptable toxicity.

 PROJECTED ACCRUAL: A total of 38-98 patients will be accrued for this study within 2 years.

